column17: Charterers to Provide ­ See Clause No. 47
column28: Off Hire ­ See also Clause No.51
column41: Bills of Lading ­ see also Clause No.48, No.77 and No.81

column3: Code Name "NYPE 93" Recommended by: The Baltic and International Maritime Council (BIMCO) The Federation of National Associations of Ship Brokers and Agents (FONASBA)
column4: TIME CHARTER, New York Produce Exchange Form, Issued by the Association of Ship Brokers and Agents (U.S.A), Inc. November 6 th, 1913 ­Amended October 20th, 1921; August 6th, 1931; October 3rd 1946 Revised June 12th, 1981; September 14th 1993.
column5: THIS CHARTER PARTY, made and concluded in Geneva this 29th day of June 2017 Between Panamanian, Singaporean or Hong Kong subsidiary company guaranteed by Nissen Kaiun Co., Ltd. or its group company, or Nissen group company itself registered in Singapore, as Owners of the Vessel described below, and Cargill International S.A., Switzerland, as Charterers.
column6: Charterers shall have the right to appoint "CARGILL OCEAN TRANSPORTATION SINGAPORE PTE LTD" as Charterers instead of "Cargill International S.A." under this Charter Party, subject to Owners' prior consent, which is not to be unreasonably withheld.
column7: One (1) unit of about 180,000 MT Type Bulk Carrier to be built by Yangzijiang Shipbuilding Ltd. (hereinafter called the "Builder"). Description of the Vessel is attached as Appendix A. Name of the Vessel to be decided. Vessel to be Dunkirk East suitable in term of Vessel’s beam and Dunkirk East suitable as far as air draft, water line to top of hatch coaming is concerned (max 13.7 m).
column8:
he Owners agree to let and the Charterers agree to hire the Vessel from the time of delivery for a period of Firm five (5) years (hereinafter called the "Firm Period"), plus one (1) year (hereinafter called "1st Optional Year"), plus one (1) year (hereinafter called "2nd Optional Year") with forty­five (45) days more or less, applicable to final year only in Charterers' option. 1st Optional Year to be declared within the end of 57th month and to commence from the end of 60th month counting from delivery of the Vessel under this Charter Party.
2nd Optional Year to be declared within the end of 69th month and to commence from the end of 72nd month counting from delivery of the Vessel under this Charter Party.
column9:
The Vessel shall be placed at the disposal of the Charterers at on dropping dock Master of the Builder’s yard in People's Republic of China, at any time, day and night, Sundays and Holidays included, subject to the successful delivery of the Vessel from the Builder to the Owners.
The Vessel on her delivery shall be ready to receive cargo with clean­swept holds (see also Clause No.46) and tight, staunch, strong and in every way fitted for ordinary cargo service, having water ballast. The Owners shall give the Charterers not less than 60/45/30/20/15/10/7/5 days approximate notices of delivery and 3/2/1 day(s) definite notice of delivery by fax/e­mail.In case of any change in delivery date in respect of latest delivery notice given, then Owners to promptly inform Charterers of that delivery date change.
column10:
Prior to redelivery the parties shall, unless otherwise agreed, appoint an independent surveyors, No on hire survey to be held since the Vessel is a new building. Quantity of bunkers	43 
remaining on board at the time of delivery under this Charter Party to be ascertained by the Master. A report shall be prepared on each occasion and signed by surveyor, Cost of off hire survey to be equally shared between Owners and Charterers.
column11: Permissible cargo under this Charter Party to be coal, iron ore pellets, iron ore lump, iron ore concentrates, iron ore fines, manganese ore, manganese ore concentrates, provided carried in accordance with IMO Regulation/Recommendation and Vessel's Classification. When loading Manganese ore concentrates, the same to be stowed, in accordance with the relevant rules, IMDG code and IMSBC Code requirements. Bauxite shall be permitted provided that the Charterers shall not claim the result of hold inspection just before loading of Bauxite. The Charterers shall inform the Owners/Master of the composition of the cargo before loading. Charterers to have the option to load other cargoes not listed above subject to Owners' prior approval which not to be unreasonably withheld but always within Vessel's physical and operating capacity.
column12: On deck cargo not to be allowed.
column13:
The Vessel shall be employed in Worldwide trading such lawful trades always via safe port(s), safe berth(s), safe anchorage(s), and safe places where she can safely lie, always afloat at all times of tide within Institute Warranty Limits excluding Israel, Iran, Iraq, Cambodia, N orth Korea, Albania, Sierra Leone (except Freetown and Pepel. For Pepel loading, Charterers to bear the expense for P&I survey for loading iron ore fines), Somalia, Eritrea, Cuba, Rep. of Djibouti, D.R.C. (i.e. former Zaire), Angola, Haiti, Lebanon, Syria, Liberia, Nigeria, Tanzania, Mozambique (except Maputo, Beira, Nacala), Turkish Occupied Cyprus, Serbia­ Montenegro and any area(s) and/or countries banned and boycotted by UN and or USA, war or war­ like zone and any other countries prohibited from calling by the flag state.

Should the political, social and/or other situation in any of the excluded countries improved to the extent not to affect the normal trading of the Vessel, then at Charterers's request in writing, Owners shall allow the Vessel to trade such countries subject to Owners' prior consent which shall not be unreasonably withheld.

Should the political, social and/or other situation in the countries of allowed trading area become worse and affect the normal trading of the Vessel then, at Owners' request in writing, such countries shall be excluded subject to Charterers' prior consent which shall not be unreasonably withheld.

The Vessel shall not trade directly between People's Republic of China and Taiwan.

Should the Charterers trade the Vessel to port(s) of Japan, Korea, China, Russian Pacific Ports or any other Country(ies) which is (are) determined as high risk port(s) for contamination of Asian Gypsy Moth by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and/or Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) and/or other Country(ies) which require Certificate of Freedom from Asian Gypsy Moth such as Australia, New Zealand and Chile, the Charterers shall carry out the inspection to obtain Certificate of Freedom from Asian Gypsy Moth to be approved by USDA and/or CFIA and/or any relevant other Country(ies) which require Certificate of Freedom of Asian Gypsy Moths, at their time and expense. In case the Certificate of Freedom from Asian Gypsy Moth cannot be obtained, any loss of time and expenses caused shall be borne by the Charterers. Notwithstanding the issuing of such a certificate, should an infestation of Asian Gypsy Moth be found or suspected, Charterers shall be responsible for any consequences whatsoever, including but not limited to costs and third party liabilities. The Vessel shall remain on hire throughout.
Charterers to redeliver the Vessel free of Asian Gypsy Moth. If the Vessel has traded to an area where there is a risk of infestation by Asian Gypsy Moth, Charterers shall, on redelivery, provide an Asian Gypsy Moth Free Certificate dated no earlier than the date of departure from the last port of call in such area.
NAABSA not to be applied. 

Breaking Institute Warranty Limits (I.W.L.) Charterers are to have the option to instruct the Vessel to break Institute Warranty Limits subject to the Owners prior consent which shall not be unreasonably withheld.

Charterers are to reimburse to Owners any additional insurance premium actually imposed by the Vessel’s Underwriters as a consequence of a breach of I.W.L.
War Risk- Subject to prior consent of the Owners which not to be unreasonably withheld, Charterers may trade the Vessel to the Countries or areas where the Additional War Risk Insurance Premium is imposed. Charterers to reimburse Additional War Risk Premium for Hull and Machinery, Loss of Hire, Blocking and Trapping and the crew war bonus if any against presentation of photo copy of vouchers from Owners' underwriters.
column14: The Vessel shall be employed in Worldwide trading such lawful trades always via safe port(s), safe berth(s), safe anchorage(s), and safe places where she can safely lie, always afloat at all times of tide within Institute Warranty Limits
column15: Trades excluding Israel, Iran, Iraq, Cambodia, N orth Korea, Albania, Sierra Leone (except Freetown and Pepel. For Pepel loading, Charterers to bear the expense for P&I survey for loading iron ore fines), Somalia, Eritrea, Cuba, Rep. of Djibouti, D.R.C. (i.e. former Zaire), Angola, Haiti, Lebanon, Syria, Liberia, Nigeria, Tanzania, Mozambique (except Maputo, Beira, Nacala), Turkish Occupied Cyprus, Serbia­ Montenegro and any area(s) and/or countries banned and boycotted by UN and or USA, war or war­ like zone and any other countries prohibited from calling by the flag state.
column16:
The Owners shall provide and pay for the insurance of the Vessel, except as otherwise provided, and for all provisions, cabin, deck, engine­room and other necessary stores, including boiler water, fresh water but	excluding those for hold cleaning. The Vessel shall operate fresh water generator during the sea passage in full capacity; Owners shall pay for
wages, immigration and consular shipping and discharging fees of the crew and charges for port services pertaining to the crew; Owners shall maintain the Vessel's class and keep her in a thoroughly efficient state in hull, machinery and equipment with all certificates, for and during the service, necessary to comply at all ports of call and canals within trading limits agreed in this Charter Party, and Owners have a full complement of officers and crew.
Fumigations ordered because of illness of the crew shall be for the Owners' account.
column17:
The Charterers, while the Vessel is on hire, shall provide and pay for all the bunkers except as otherwise agreed; shall pay for port charges (including compulsory watchmen and cargo watchmen and compulsory garbage disposal),  compulsory,	customary pilotages, towages, agencies, commissions, consular charges (except those pertaining to individual crew members
or flag of the Vessel), and all other usual expenses except those stated in Clause 6 , but when the Vessel puts into a port for causes for which the Vessel is responsible (other than by stress of weather), then all	such charges incurred shall be paid by the Owners. Fumigations ordered because of cargoes carried or ports visited while the Vessel is employed under this Charter Party shall be for the Charterers' account. All other fumigations	
shall be for the Charterers' account after the Vessel has been on charter for a continuous period of six months or more. 
The Charterers shall provide and pay for necessary dunnage and also any extra fittings requisite for a special trade or unusual cargo, but the Owners shall allow them the use of any dunnage already aboard the Vessel. Prior to redelivery the Charterers shall remove their dunnage and fittings at their cost and in their time.	
Tonnage dues certificates (such as but not limited to Chinese Tonnage Certificate) to be for Charterers' account.
column18:
(a) The Master shall perform the voyages with due despatch, and shall render all customary assistance with the Vessel's crew. The Master and all Officers shall be conversant with the English language and (although appointed by the Owners) shall be under the orders and directions of the Charterers as regards	employment and agency; and the Charterers shall perform all cargo handling, including but not limited to loading, stowing, trimming, lashing, securing, dunnaging, unlashing, discharging, and tallying, at their risk and expense, under the supervision and direction of the Master.

(b) If the Charterers shall have reasonable cause to be dissatisfied with the conduct of the Master or officers, the Owners shall, on receiving particulars of the complaint, investigate the same, and, if necessary, make a change in the appointments.
column19:
(b) The Charterers shall supply bunkers of a quality suitable for burning in the Vessel's engines	and auxiliaries and which conform to the specification(s) as set out in Appendix A.
Alternative Bunker Specification- Charterers shall supply bunkers of the agreed specifications and grades (IFO IF­380CST) ISO 8217 2005 RMG380 and MDO ISO 8217 2005 DMB) as per description of the Vessel in Annex A. Charterers have the right to supply Vessel with IFO 180 CST at places where 380 CST is not available.Owners accept local bunker specifications in South Africa (IFO RMF 25), Brazil, Egypt, India, Taiwan as long as same are being supplied by internationally recognized bunker suppliers and comply with MARPOL Annex VI Rule 18 and subject to Charterers presenting such local bunker specification to Owners and Owners approve such local bunker specification in advance to the bunkering. The Charterers shall hold the Owners harmless from any damage caused by using such local bunker. The Owners guarantee that the Vessel is eligible for bunkers in the United States of America and in any other country.
The Owners reserve their right to make a claim against the Charterers for any damage to the main engines or the auxiliaries caused by the use of unsuitable fuels or fuels not complying with the agreed	specification(s) (as set out in Appendix A). Additionally, if bunker fuels supplied do not conform with the mutually agreed specification(s) or otherwise prove unsuitable for burning in the Vessel's engines or auxiliaries, the Owners shall not be held responsible for any reduction in the Vessel's speed performance and/or increased bunker consumption, nor for any time lost and any other consequences.
column20:
The Charterers shall pay for the use and hire of the said Vessel at the following rate.
Firm period- US$14,750 per day or pro­rata including overtime,

1st Optional Period: US$15,000 per day or pro­rata including overtime, 

2nd Optional Period: US$15,500 per day or pro­rata including overtime.

No address commission to Charterers.
column21:
Hire shall be continuously paid to Owners (unless Vessel lost) until the time of the day of her redelivery in like good order and condition, ordinary wear and tear excepted, on dropping last outward sea pilot at one (1) safe port within Japan/Singapore range including Indonesia, Taiwan, South Korea, People's Republic of China or Skaw/Passero range, including U.K. and Eire, or passing either points or Aden/passing Muscat outbound or Boston/Galveston range, always within Institute Warranty Limits (I.W.L.) and permitted countries/areas under the Charter Party, excluding war or warlike zone(s), port in Charterers' option at any time, day or night, Sundays and Holidays included, unless otherwise mutually agreed.	
The Charterers shall give the Owners not less than 30/20 approximate and 15/10/4/3/2/1	days definite notice in writing of the Vessel's expected date and probable port of redelivery.	
For the purpose of hire calculations, the times of delivery, redelivery or termination of charter shall be adjusted to GMT.
column22:
(a) Payment
Payment of Hire shall be made so as to be received net by the Owners or their designated payee in their designated bank , which is to be advised later in United States Currency, in funds available to the Owners on the due date,  monthly in advance, and for the last month or part of same the approximate amount of hire, and should same not cover the actual time, hire shall be paid for the expected balance of period. Failing the punctual and regular payment of the hire, or on any fundamental breach whatsoever of this Charter Party, the Owners shall be at liberty to withdraw the Vessel from the service of the Charterers without prejudice to any claims they (the Owners) may otherwise have on the Charterers. At any time after the expiry of the grace period provided in Sub­clause 11 (b) hereunder and while the hire is outstanding, the Owners shall, without prejudice to the liberty to withdraw, be entitled to withhold the performance of any and all of their obligations hereunder and shall have no responsibility whatsoever for any consequences thereof, in respect of which the Charterers hereby indemnify the Owners, and hire shall continue to accrue and any extra expenses resulting from such withholding shall be for the Charterers' account.

(b) Grace Period- Where there is failure to make punctual and regular payment of hire due to oversight, negligence, errors or omissions on the part of the Charterers or their bankers, the Charterers shall be given by the Owners three (3) clear banking days (as recognized at the agreed place of payment) written notice to rectify the failure, and when so rectified within those three (3)	days following the Owners' notice, the payment shall stand as regular and punctual. Failure by the Charterers to pay the hire within three (3) banking	days of their receiving the Owners' notice as provided herein, shall entitle the Owners to withdraw as set forth in Sub­clause 11 (a) above. 

(c) Last Hire Payment	- 
Should the Vessel be on her voyage towards port of redelivery at the time the last and/or the penultimate payment of hire is/are due, said payment(s) is/are to be made for such length of time as being the estimated time necessary to complete the voyage, and taking into account bunkers actually on board, to be taken over by the Owners and estimated disbursements for	
the Owners' account before redelivery. Should same not cover the actual time, hire is to be paid for the expected balance of period, as it becomes due. When the Vessel has been redelivered, any difference is to be refunded by the Owners or paid by the Charterers, as the case may be.	

(d) Cash Advances	

Cash for the Vessel's ordinary disbursements at any port may be advanced by the Charterers, as required by the Owners, subject to 2½ percent commission and such advances shall be deducted from the hire. The Charterers, however, shall in no way be responsible for the application of such advances. In case required by Owners' Financier, Charterers to sign Acknowledgement of Assignment for Charter Hire and Charter Party based on Owners’ Financer’s wording.
column23: The Vessel shall be loaded and discharged in any safe dock or at any safe berth or safe anchorage or safe place that Charterers or their agents may direct, provided the Vessel can safely enter, lie and depart always afloat No NAABSA is allowed.
column24:
(a) The whole reach of the Vessel's holds,  no cargoes to be loaded on deck, and other cargo spaces (not more than she can
reasonably and safely stow and carry), including accommodations for supercargo, if carried, shall be at the Charterers' disposal, reserving only proper and sufficient space for the Vessel's officers, crew, tackle, apparel, furniture, provisions, stores and fuel.
column25: The Charterers are entitled to appoint a supercargo, who shall accompany the Vessel at the Charterers'risk and see that voyages are performed with due despatch. He is to be furnished with free accommodation and same fare as provided for the Master's table, the Charterers paying at the rate of U.S.$ 15.00	per day. The Owners shall victual pilots and customs officers, and also, when authorized by the Charterers or their agents, shall victual tally clerks, stevedore's foreman, etc.,See also Clause No.47
column26: The Charterers shall furnish the Master from time to time with all requisite instructions and sailing directions, in writing, in the English language, and the Master shall keep full and correct deck and engine logs of the voyage or voyages, which are to be patent to the Charterers or their agents, and furnish the Charterers, their agents or supercargo, when required, with a true copy of such deck and engine logs, showing the course of the Vessel, distance run and the consumption of bunkers. Any log extracts required by the Charterers shall be in the English language.
column27: If required by the Charterers, time shall not commence before 00:01 hours local time of 1st October, 2019 and should the Vessel not be ready for delivery on or before 23:59 hours local time of 31st March, 2020 in Owners' option, the Charterers shall have the option of cancelling this Charter Party. Owners to narrow the laydays to three (3) months spread latest six (6) months prior to the expected delivery of the Vessel. Should the completion of the construction of the Vessel is delayed due to the cause not attributable to Owners, including but not limited to the cause categorized as force majeure in the Shipbuilding Contract, the cancelling date under the Charter Party can be postponed automatically for such number of the days of delay to a maximum of 210 days. For delay beyond that, Owners and Charterers to discuss for a mutual agreement according to below clauses, (a) Should the Vessel not be ready to be delivered on the agreed cancelling date (extended of 210 days), Charterers shall have the option of cancelling this Charter Party without any compensation between Owners and Charterers.(b) Should Owners anticipate that, despite the exercise of due diligence, the Vessel will not be ready to deliver by the cancelling date (extended of 210 days), Owners shall notify Charterers thereof without delay stating the expected date of the Vessel’s readiness to deliver and asking whether Charterers will exercise their option of cancelling the Charter Party, or agree to a new cancelling date. Such option (either (a) or (b)) must be declared by Charterers within 10 working days after the receipt of Owners’ notice. The provisions of sub­clause (b) of this clause shall operate only once, and in case of the Vessel’s further delay, Charterers shall have the option of cancelling the Charter Party as per sub­clause (a) of this clause.
column28:
In the event of loss of time from deficiency and/or default and/or strike of officers or crew, or deficiency of stores, fire, breakdown of, or damages to hull, machinery or equipment, grounding, detention by the arrest of the Vessel, (unless such arrest is caused by events for which the Charterers, sub­charterers, their servants, agents or subcontractors are responsible), or detention by average accidents to the Vessel or cargo unless resulting from inherent vice, quality or defect of the cargo, drydocking for the purpose of examination or 	
painting bottom, or by any other similar cause whatsoever preventing the full working of the Vessel, the payment of hire and overtime, if any, shall cease for the time thereby lost. Should the Vessel deviate or put back during a voyage, contrary to the orders or directions of the Charterers, for any reason other than accident to the cargo or where permitted in lines 257 to 258 hereunder, the hire is to be suspended from the time of her deviating or putting back until she is again in the same or equidistant position from the destination and the voyage resumed therefrom. All bunkers used by the Vessel while off hire shall be for the Owners' account. In the event of the Vessel being driven into port or to anchorage through stress of weather, trading to shallow harbors or to rivers or ports with bars, any detention of the Vessel and/or expenses resulting from such detention shall be for the Charterers' account. If upon the voyage the speed be reduced by defect in, or breakdown of, any part of her hull, machinery or equipment, the time so lost, and	the cost of any extra bunkers consumed in consequence thereof, and all extra proven expenses may be deducted from the hire. Any delay by ice or time spent in quarantine due to port(s) visited shall be for Charterers' account.
column29: Unless otherwise agreed, the Charterers shall have the liberty to sublet the Vessel for all or any part of the time covered by this Charter Party, but the Charterers remain responsible for the fulfillment of this Charter Party.
column30:
Owners shall have the option to place the Vessel in drydock during the currency of this Charter Party at intervals of every about 24­30 months at a convenient time and place to be mutually agreed between Owners and Charterers for bottom cleaning and painting and/or repairs as required by Classification Society or directed by circumstances. Owners shall give Charterers six (6) months prior notice of approximate timing they intend to drydock the Vessel, except for emergency case and Charterers shall endeavour to bring the Vessel back to Japan/Singapore range for such drydocking.
The off­hire period shall be the balance period between the actual time elapsed (last discharging port
­ dock ­ first nominated port) and the estimated time required under the artificial voyage going straight from the last discharging port to first nominated port. The bunker consumed to be calculated in the same manner, unless otherwise mutually agreed.
column31: Should the Vessel be lost, money paid in advance and not earned (reckoning from the date of loss or	being last heard of) shall be returned to the Charterers at once.
column32: The act of God, enemies, fire, restraint of princes, rulers and people, and all dangers and accidents of the seas, rivers, machinery, boilers, and navigation, and errors of navigation throughout this Charter, always	mutually excepted.
column33: The Vessel shall have the liberty to sail with or without pilots, to tow and to be towed, to assist vessels in distress, and to deviate for the purpose of saving life and property.
column34:
The Owners shall have a lien upon all cargoes and all sub­freights and/or sub­hire for any amounts due under this Charter Party, including general average contributions, and the Charterers shall have a lien on	the Vessel for all monies paid in advance and not earned, and any overpaid hire or excess deposit to be returned at once.	The Charterers will not directly or indirectly suffer, nor permit to be continued, any lien or encumbrance, which might have priority over the title and interest of the Owners in the Vessel. The Charterers	
undertake that during the period of this Charter Party, they will not procure any supplies or necessaries or services, including any port expenses and bunkers, on the credit of the Owners or in the Owners' time.
column35: All derelicts and salvage shall be for the Owners' and the Charterers' equal benefit after deducting Owners' and Charterers' expenses and crew's proportion.
column36: General average shall be adjusted according to York­Antwerp Rules 1974, as amended 1994 in London	and settled in U.S. Dollars currency. The Charterers shall procure that all bills of lading issued during the currency of the Charter Party will contain a provision to the effect that general average shall be adjusted according to York­Antwerp Rules 1974, as amended 1994, and will include the "New Jason Clause" as per Clause 31.
column37: Nothing herein stated is to be construed as a demise of the Vessel to the Time Charterers. The Owners shall remain responsible for the navigation of the Vessel, acts of pilots and tug boats, insurance, crew, and all other matters, same as when trading for their own account.
column38: Cargo claims as between the Owners and the Charterers shall be settled in accordance with the Inter­Club New York Produce Exchange Agreement of September 1996, or any subsequent modification or replacement thereof.
column39: The Owners shall provide on the Vessel for night work lights as on board, but all additional lights and lights clusters over those on board shall be at the Charterers' expense.
column40: Overtime payments to officers and crew for work ordered by the Charterers or their agents, or local authority are to be included in the hire.
column41:
(a) The Master shall sign the bills of lading or waybills for cargo as presented in conformity with mates or tally clerk's receipts. However, the Charterers or authorized Charterers' Agents may sign bills of lading or waybills on behalf of the Master, with the Master's prior written authority, always in conformity with mates or tally clerk's receipts.

Charterers shall indemnify Owners and are fully responsible for all consequences when the Bills of Lading or Sea Waybill issued by Charterers or their agent are not in conformity with mates or tally clerk's receipt. When Charterers issue and sign Sea Waybills, Owners and Master shall release cargoes in accordance with Charterers and/or agent's instructions. Charterers hereby indemnify Owners and the Master against any consequences whatsoever that may arise from above.

(b) All bills of lading or waybills shall be without prejudice to this Charter Party and the Charterers shall indemnify the Owners against all consequences or liabilities which may arise from any inconsistency between this Charter Party and any bills of lading or waybills signed by the Charterers or by the Master at their request.

(c) Charterers have the option to use their Bills of Lading forms only if Owners P & I Club approves the same.
column42:
This Charter Party is subject to the following clauses all of which are also to be included in all bills of lading	or waybills issued hereunder:	

(a) CLAUSE PARAMOUNT ­ See Clause No. 67	
    NA
and	
(b) BOTH­TO­BLAME COLLISION CLAUSE	
"If the ship comes into collision with another ship as a result of the negligence of the other ship and any act, neglect or default of the master, mariner, pilot or the servants of the carrier in the navigation or in the management of the ship, the owners of the goods carried hereunder will indemnify the carrier against	
all loss or liability to the other or non­carrying ship or her owners insofar as such loss or liability represents loss of, or damage to, or any claim whatsoever of the owners of said goods, paid or payable by the other or non­carrying ship or her owners to the owners of said goods and set off, recouped or recovered by the	
other or non­carrying ship or her owners as part of their claim against the carrying ship or carrier. The foregoing provisions shall also apply where the owners, operators or those in charge of any ships or objects other than, or in addition to, the colliding ships or objects are at fault in respect to a collision or contact."	
and	
(c) NEW JASON CLAUSE	

"In the event of accident, danger, damage or disaster before or after the commencement of the voyage resulting from any cause whatsoever, whether due to negligence or not, for which, or for the consequences of which, the carrier is not responsible, by statute, contract, or otherwise, the goods, shippers, consignees, or owners of the goods shall contribute with the carrier in general average to the	
payment of any sacrifices, losses, or expenses of a general average nature that may be made or incurred, and shall pay salvage and special charges incurred in respect of the goods. If a salving ship is owned or operated by the carrier, salvage shall be paid for as fully as if salving ship	or ships belonged to strangers. Such deposit as the carrier or his agents may deem sufficient to cover the estimated contribution of the goods and any salvage and special charges thereon shall, if required, be made by the goods, shippers, consignees or owners of the goods to the carrier before delivery." 
and	

(d) U.S. TRADE ­ DRUG CLAUSE	354

"In pursuance of the provisions of the U.S. Anti Drug Abuse Act 1986 or any re­enactment thereof, the Charterers warrant to exercise the highest degree of care and diligence in preventing unmanifested narcotic drugs and marijuana to be loaded or concealed on board the Vessel. Non­compliance with the provisions of this clause shall amount to breach of warranty for consequences of which the Charterers shall be liable and shall hold the Owners, the Master and the crew of the Vessel harmless and shall keep them indemnified against all claims whatsoever which may arise and be made	against them individually or jointly. Furthermore, all time lost and all expenses incurred, including fines, as a result of the Charterers' breach of the provisions of this clause shall be for the Charterer's account and the Vessel shall remain on hire.	
Should the Vessel be arrested as a result of the Charterers' non­compliance with the provisions of this clause, the Charterers shall at their expense take all reasonable steps to secure that within a reasonable time the Vessel is released and at their expense put up the bails to secure release of the Vessel.
The Owners shall remain responsible for all time lost and all expenses incurred, including fines, in the	event that unmanifested narcotic drugs of any kind including and marijuana are found in the possession or effects of the Vessel's personnel."

and	
(e) WAR CLAUSES ­ See Clause No. 79 "CONWARTIME 1993"	371

"(i) No contraband of war shall be shipped. The Vessel shall not be required, without the consent of the Owners, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, to enter any port or zone which is involved in a state of war, warlike operations, or hostilities, civil strife, insurrection or piracy whether there be a declaration	
of war or not, where the Vessel, cargo or crew might reasonably be expected to be subject to capture, seizure or arrest, or to a hostile act by a belligerent power (the term "power" meaning any de jure or defacto authority or any purported governmental organization maintaining naval, military or air forces).	

(ii) If such consent is given by the Owners, the Charterers will pay the provable additional cost of insuring the Vessel against hull war risks in an amount equal to the value under her ordinary hull policy but not exceeding a valuation of In addition, the Owners may purchase and the Charterers will pay for war risk insurance on ancillary risks such as loss of hire, freight disbursements,	
total loss, blocking and trapping, etc. If such insurance is not obtainable commercially or through a government program, the Vessel shall not be required to enter or remain at any such port or zone.

(iii) In the event of the existence of the conditions described in (i) subsequent to the date of this Charter, or while the Vessel is on hire under this Charter, the Charterers shall, in respect of voyages to any such port or zone assume the provable additional cost of wages and insurance properly incurred in connection	
with master, officers and crew as a consequence of such war, warlike operations or hostilities.

Trades excluding Israel, Iran, Iraq, Cambodia, North Korea, Albania, Somalia, Eritrea, Cuba, Angola, Haiti, Lebanon, Syria, Liberia, Nigeria, Tanzania, Mozambique, Turkish Occupied Cyprus, Serbia-Montenegro, Russian Pacific ports, and any area(s) and/or countries banned and boycotted by UN and or USA, war or war-like zone and any other countries prohibited from calling by the flag state. the normal trading of the vessel, then, at Charterers' request in writing, Owners shall allow the vessel to trade such countries subject to Owners' prior consent which shall not be unreasonably withheld. (a) Payment
Payment of Hire shall be made so as to be received net by the Owners or their designated payee in their designated bank , which is to be advised later in United States Currency, in funds available to the Owners on the due date,  monthly in advance, and for the last month or part of same the approximate amount of hire, and should same not cover the actual time, hire shall be paid for the expected balance of period. Failing the punctual and regular payment of the hire, or on any fundamental breach whatsoever of this Charter Party, the Owners shall be at liberty to withdraw the Vessel from the service of the Charterers without prejudice to any claims they (the Owners) may otherwise have on the Charterers. At any time after the expiry of the grace period provided in Sub­clause 11 (b) hereunder and while the hire is outstanding, the Owners shall, without prejudice to the liberty to withdraw, be entitled to withhold the performance of any and all of their obligations hereunder and shall have no responsibility whatsoever for any consequences thereof, in respect of which the Charterers hereby indemnify the Owners, and hire shall continue to accrue and any extra expenses resulting from such withholding shall be for the Charterers' account.

(b) Grace Period- Where there is failure to make punctual and regular payment of hire due to oversight, negligence, errors or omissions on the part of the Charterers or their bankers, the Charterers shall be given by the Owners three (3) clear banking days (as recognized at the agreed place of payment) written notice to rectify the failure, and when so rectified within those three (3)	days following the Owners' notice, the payment shall stand as regular and punctual. Failure by the Charterers to pay the hire within three (3) banking	days of their receiving the Owners' notice as provided herein, shall entitle the Owners to withdraw as set forth in Sub­clause 11 (a) above. 

(c) Last Hire Payment	- 
Should the Vessel be on her voyage towards port of redelivery at the time the last and/or the penultimate payment of hire is/are due, said payment(s) is/are to be made for such length of time as being the estimated time necessary to complete the voyage, and taking into account bunkers actually on board, to be taken over by the Owners and estimated disbursements for	
the Owners' account before redelivery. Should same not cover the actual time, hire is to be paid for the expected balance of period, as it becomes due. When the Vessel has been redelivered, any difference is to be refunded by the Owners or paid by the Charterers, as the case may be.	

(d) Cash Advances	

Cash for the Vessel's ordinary disbursements at any port may be advanced by the Charterers, as required by the Owners, subject to 2½ percent commission and such advances shall be deducted from the hire. The Charterers, however, shall in no way be responsible for the application of such advances. In case required by Owners' Financier, Charterers to sign Acknowledgement of Assignment for Charter Hire and Charter Party based on Owners’ Financer’s wording.

This Charter Party is subject to the following clauses all of which are also to be included in all bills of lading	or waybills issued hereunder:	

(a) CLAUSE PARAMOUNT ­ See Clause No. 67	
    NA
and	
(b) BOTH­TO­BLAME COLLISION CLAUSE	
"If the ship comes into collision with another ship as a result of the negligence of the other ship and any act, neglect or default of the master, mariner, pilot or the servants of the carrier in the navigation or in the management of the ship, the owners of the goods carried hereunder will indemnify the carrier against	
all loss or liability to the other or non­carrying ship or her owners insofar as such loss or liability represents loss of, or damage to, or any claim whatsoever of the owners of said goods, paid or payable by the other or non­carrying ship or her owners to the owners of said goods and set off, recouped or recovered by the	
other or non­carrying ship or her owners as part of their claim against the carrying ship or carrier. The foregoing provisions shall also apply where the owners, operators or those in charge of any ships or objects other than, or in addition to, the colliding ships or objects are at fault in respect to a collision or contact."	
and	
(c) NEW JASON CLAUSE	

"In the event of accident, danger, damage or disaster before or after the commencement of the voyage resulting from any cause whatsoever, whether due to negligence or not, for which, or for the consequences of which, the carrier is not responsible, by statute, contract, or otherwise, the goods, shippers, consignees, or owners of the goods shall contribute with the carrier in general average to the	
payment of any sacrifices, losses, or expenses of a general average nature that may be made or incurred, and shall pay salvage and special charges incurred in respect of the goods. If a salving ship is owned or operated by the carrier, salvage shall be paid for as fully as if salving ship	or ships belonged to strangers. Such deposit as the carrier or his agents may deem sufficient to cover the estimated contribution of the goods and any salvage and special charges thereon shall, if required, be made by the goods, shippers, consignees or owners of the goods to the carrier before delivery." 
and	

(d) U.S. TRADE ­ DRUG CLAUSE	354

"In pursuance of the provisions of the U.S. Anti Drug Abuse Act 1986 or any re­enactment thereof, the Charterers warrant to exercise the highest degree of care and diligence in preventing unmanifested narcotic drugs and marijuana to be loaded or concealed on board the Vessel. Non­compliance with the provisions of this clause shall amount to breach of warranty for consequences of which the Charterers shall be liable and shall hold the Owners, the Master and the crew of the Vessel harmless and shall keep them indemnified against all claims whatsoever which may arise and be made	against them individually or jointly. Furthermore, all time lost and all expenses incurred, including fines, as a result of the Charterers' breach of the provisions of this clause shall be for the Charterer's account and the Vessel shall remain on hire.	
Should the Vessel be arrested as a result of the Charterers' non­compliance with the provisions of this clause, the Charterers shall at their expense take all reasonable steps to secure that within a reasonable time the Vessel is released and at their expense put up the bails to secure release of the Vessel.
The Owners shall remain responsible for all time lost and all expenses incurred, including fines, in the	event that unmanifested narcotic drugs of any kind including and marijuana are found in the possession or effects of the Vessel's personnel."

and	
(e) WAR CLAUSES ­ See Clause No. 79 "CONWARTIME 1993"	371

"(i) No contraband of war shall be shipped. The Vessel shall not be required, without the consent of the Owners, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, to enter any port or zone which is involved in a state of war, warlike operations, or hostilities, civil strife, insurrection or piracy whether there be a declaration	
of war or not, where the Vessel, cargo or crew might reasonably be expected to be subject to capture, seizure or arrest, or to a hostile act by a belligerent power (the term "power" meaning any de jure or defacto authority or any purported governmental organization maintaining naval, military or air forces).	

(ii) If such consent is given by the Owners, the Charterers will pay the provable additional cost of insuring the Vessel against hull war risks in an amount equal to the value under her ordinary hull policy but not exceeding a valuation of In addition, the Owners may purchase and the Charterers will pay for war risk insurance on ancillary risks such as loss of hire, freight disbursements,	
total loss, blocking and trapping, etc. If such insurance is not obtainable commercially or through a government program, the Vessel shall not be required to enter or remain at any such port or zone.

(iii) In the event of the existence of the conditions described in (i) subsequent to the date of this Charter, or while the Vessel is on hire under this Charter, the Charterers shall, in respect of voyages to any such port or zone assume the provable additional cost of wages and insurance properly incurred in connection	
with master, officers and crew as a consequence of such war, warlike operations or hostilities.	

(iv) Any war bonus to officers and crew due to the Vessel's trading or cargo carried shall be for the Charterers' account."

Either the Owners or the Charterers may cancel this Charter Party. Whereupon, the Charterers shall redeliver the Vessel to the Owners in accordance with Clause 10 ; if she has cargo on board, after discharge thereof at destination, or, if debarred under this Clause from reaching or entering it, at a near open and safe port as directed by the Owners; or, if she has no cargo on board, at the port at which she then is; or, if at sea, at a near open and safe port as directed by the Owners. The Charterers shall provide and pay extra for sweeping and/or washing and/or cleaning of holds between voyages and/or between cargoes and washing if required taking ballast into cargo hold in order to keep necessary air draft in port provided such work can be undertaken by the crew and is permitted by 
local regulations, at the rate of U.S.$ 400.00/hold for sweeping and U.S.$ 500.00/hold for washing. Such extra hold cleaning bonus to be paid to Owners via hire payment.
Other various crew bonus to be agreed later. In connection with any such operation, the Owners shall not be responsible if the Vessel's holds are not accepted or passed by the port or any other authority unless the Vessel has been rejected because of rust scale in which case the Vessel to be put in off hire until Owners effect at their expenses and with the utmost despatch all the necessary works to have the Vessel passed. The Charterers shall have the option to re­deliver the Vessel with unclean/upswept holds against a lumpsum payment of U.S.$ 8,000.00 in lieu of cleaning.
column46: Any U.S. Gross Transportation Tax as enacted by the United States Public Law 99­514, (also referred to as The U.S. Tax Reform Act of 1986), including later changes or amendments, levied on income attributable to transportation under this Charter Party which begins or ends in the United States, and which income under the laws of the United States is treated as U.S. source gross transportation income of Owners and is not exempt or eligible for exemption from tax under section 883 of the U.S. Internal Revenue Code, an applicable tax treaty or otherwise, shall be reimbursed by the Charterers to Owners upon reasonable proof by Owners to Charterers of Owners' payment of the tax. Reasonable proof may include a copy of the relevant portions of any tax returns filed by Owners in the U.S. Notwithstanding anything whatsoever in the foregoing to the contrary, Owners may not claim reimbursement or any such tax paid in the U.S. to the extent that tax payment was available to offset or reduce Owners’ tax liability in any other jurisdiction in which Owners are subject to tax.

If known, Charterers shall declare or serve a notice to Owners of their intention to keep the Vessel in the same port for more than 30 days well in advance before the Vessel's entering into such port. Provided such notice has been served, the Charterers shall have the benefit of any return insurance premium receivable by the Owners from their underwriters as and when received from underwriters by reason of the Vessel being in port for a minimum Period of 30 days provided the Vessel 
remains on hire.
If the Vessel stayed in a port for more than 30 consecutive days, as directed by the Charterers and when bottom fouling is anticipated, Charterers are to position the Vessel to a safe anchorage where Owners can carry out bottom cleaning at Charterers' time and expense. Place where to carry out bottom cleaning to be mutually agreed. Unless such bottom cleaning is carried out, Charterers are not entitled to lodge speed performance claim to the Owners.

(b) LONDON	

All disputes arising out of or in connection with this Charter Party shall be arbitrated in London in accordance with the rules of the London Maritime Arbitrators Association and, unless the parties agree forthwith on a single Arbitrator, be referred to the final arbitrament of two Arbitrators carrying on business in London who shall be members of the Baltic Mercantile & Shipping Exchange and engaged in Shipping, one to be appointed by each of the parties, with power to such Arbitrators to appoint an Umpire. No award shall be questioned or invalidated on the ground that any of the Arbitrators is not qualified as 
above, unless objection to his action be taken before the award is made. Any dispute arising hereunder shall be governed by English Law.
For disputes where the total amount claimed by either party does not exceed US $ 50.000.­ ** the arbitration shall be conducted in accordance with the Small Claims Procedure of the London Maritime Arbitrators Association.

as it becomes due, if so required by the Owners. Failing the punctual and regular payment of the hire,	149

or omissions on the part of the Charterers or their bankers, the Charterers shall be given by the Owners	161

If required by the Charterers, time shall not commence before 00:01 hours local time of 1st October, 2019 and should the
Vessel not be ready for delivery on or before 23:59 hours local time of 31st March, 2020 in Owners' option but not later than   hours,
the Charterers shall have the option of cancelling this Charter Party.
Owners to narrow the laydays to three (3) months spread latest six (6) months prior to the expected delivery of the Vessel.
Should the completion of the construction of the Vessel is delayed due to the cause not attributable to Owners, including but not limited to the cause categorized as force majeure in the Shipbuilding Contract, the cancelling date under the Charter Party can be postponed automatically for such

number of the days of delay to a maximum of 210 days. For delay beyond that, Owners and Charterers to discuss for a mutual agreement according to below clauses:

(a)	Should the Vessel not be ready to be delivered on the agreed cancelling date (extended of 210 days), Charterers shall have the option of cancelling this Charter Party without any compensation between Owners and Charterers.

(b)	Should Owners anticipate that, despite the exercise of due diligence, the Vessel will not be ready to deliver by the cancelling date (extended of 210 days), Owners shall notify Charterers thereof without delay stating the expected date of the Vessel’s readiness to deliver and asking whether Charterers will exercise their option of cancelling the Charter Party, or agree to a new cancelling date.

Such option (either (a) or (b)) must be declared by Charterers within 10 working days after the receipt of Owners’ notice.

The provisions of sub­clause (b) of this clause shall operate only once, and in case of the Vessel’s further delay, Charterers shall have the option of cancelling the Charter Party as per sub­clause (a) of this clause.
Extension of Cancelling	209
If the Owners warrant that, despite the exercise of due diligence by them, the Vessel will not be ready	210
for delivery by the cancelling date, and provided the Owners are able to state with reasonable certainty	211
the date on which the Vessel will be ready, they may, at the earliest seven days before the Vessel is	212

days or by the cancelling date, whichever shall first occur, then the seventh day after the expected date	215
of readiness for delivery as notified by the Owners shall replace the original cancelling date. Should the	216
Vessel be further delayed, the Owners shall be entitled to require further declarations of the Charterers in	217
accordance with this Clause.	218

of stores, fire, breakdown of, or damages to hull, machinery or equipment, grounding, detention by the	221

222

225

during a voyage, contrary to the orders or directions of the Charterers, for any reason other than accident	227
to the cargo or where permitted in lines 257 to 258 hereunder, the hire is to be suspended from the time	228
of her deviating or putting back until she is again in the same or equidistant position from the destination	229
and the voyage resumed therefrom. All bunkers used by the Vessel while off hire shall be for the Owners'	230
account. In the event of the Vessel being driven into port or to anchorage through stress of weather,	231
trading to shallow harbors or to rivers or ports with bars, any detention of the Vessel and/or expenses	232
resulting from such detention shall be for the Charterers' account. If upon the voyage the speed be	233
reduced by defect in, or breakdown of, any part of her hull, machinery or equipment, the time so lost, and	234
the cost of any extra bunkers consumed in consequence thereof, and all extra proven expenses may be	235
 
deducted from the hire. Any delay by ice or time spent in quarantine due to port(s) visited shall be for Charterers' account.

18.	Sublet	237

the time covered by this Charter Party, but the Charterers remain responsible for the fulfillment of this	239
Charter Party.	240

The Vessel was last drydocked	242

at a convenient time and place, to be mutually agreed upon between the Owners and the Charterers, for	244
 
bottom cleaning and painting and/or repair as required by class or dictated by circumstances.

Owners shall have the option to place the Vessel in drydock during the currency of this Charter Party at intervals of every about 24­30 months at a convenient time and place to be mutually agreed between Owners and Charterers for bottom cleaning and painting and/or repairs as required by Classification Society or directed by circumstances. Owners shall give Charterers six (6) months prior notice of approximate timing they intend to drydock the Vessel, except for emergency case and Charterers shall endeavour to bring the Vessel back to Japan/Singapore range for such drydocking.

seas, rivers, machinery, boilers, and navigation, and errors of navigation throughout this Charter, always	254

column10:
A joint on-hire survey including bunkers and condition is to be held in Owners’ time at delivery port and/or first loading port but
Vessel to be remain on-hire in case survey doesn’t interfere with Charterers normal operation. A joint off-hire survey including
bunkers and condition is to be held in Charterers’ time at redelivery port. The cost of these surveys to be equally shared
between Owners and Charterers. The appointment of the surveyors is to be agreed jointly between Owners and Charterers.
column11:
Trading only with harmless coal, iron ore, and/or iron ore pellets and/or sintered iron ore, bauxite only from Guinea (Port de
Boke / Kamsar / Boffa), coke coal and manganese ore only from Brazil ports / South Africa ports / Teluk of Malaysia, always
within Vessel’s natural segregation.

All cargoes are safe to load in Vessel (being non-hazardous / non-dangerous) and to be loaded / stowed / trimmed / separated
/ discharged in accordance with IMO / International and local authorities’ latest rules, regulations, guidelines, and recommendations.

BIMCO Solid Bulk Cargoes that Can Liquefy Clause for Charter Parties
(a) The Charterers shall ensure that all solid bulk cargoes to be carried under this Charter Party are presented for carriage and
loaded always in compliance with applicable International regulations, including the International Maritime Solid Bulk Cargoes
(IMSBC) Code 2009 (as may be amended from time to time and including any recommendations approved and agreed by the
IMO).
(b) If the cargo is a solid bulk cargo that may liquefy, the Charterers shall prior to the commencement of loading provide the
ship’s Master, or his representative, with all information and documentation in accordance with the IMSBC Code, including but
not limited to a certificate of the Transportable Moisture Limit (TML), and a certificate or declaration of the moisture content,
both signed by the Shipper.
(c) The Owners shall have the right to take samples of cargo prior to loading and, at Charterers’ request, samples to be taken
jointly, testing of such cargo samples shall be conducted jointly between Charterers and Owners by an independent laboratory
that is to
be nominated by Owners. Sampling and testing shall be at the Charterers’ risk, cost, expense and time. The Master or
Owners’ representative shall at all times be permitted unrestricted and unimpeded access to cargo for sampling and testing
purposes.
If the Master, in his sole discretion using reasonable judgement, considers there is a risk arising out of or in connection with
the cargo (including but not limited to the risk of liquefaction) which could jeopardise the safety of the crew, the Vessel or the
cargo on the voyage, he shall have the right to refuse to accept the cargo or, if already loaded, refuse to sail from the loading
port or place. The Master shall have the right to require the Charterers to make safe the cargo prior to loading or, if already
loaded, to offload the cargo and replace it with a cargo acceptable to the Master, all at the Charterers’ risk, cost, expense and
time. The exercise by the Master of the aforesaid rights shall not be a breach of this Charter Party.
(d) Notwithstanding anything else contained in this Charter Party, all loss, damage, delay, expenses, costs and liabilities
whatsoever arising out of or related to complying with, or resulting from failure to comply with, such regulations or with
Charterers’ obligations hereunder shall be for the Charterers’ account. The Charterers shall indemnify the Owners against any
and all claims whatsoever against the Owners arising out of the Owners complying with the Charterers’ instructions to load the
agreed cargo.
(e) This Clause shall be without prejudice to the Charterers’ obligations under this Charter Party to provide a safe cargo. In
relation to loading, anything done or not done by the Master or the Owners in compliance with this Clause shall not amount to
a waiver of any rights of the Owners.

column13:
Trading worldwide between safe anchorages, safe berths, safe ports and places, always safely afloat, always accessible, always within I.W.L. / I.N.L., always within war risk trading warranties and excluding war and warlike zones where extra / additional war risk premium to apply and charged by Vessel’s hull Underwriters from time to time and countries which from time to time may be excluded by governing authority of the Vessel’s flag. JWC Listed Areas are always excluded.

The following countries or places are specifically excluded:

Cuba, Lebanon, Syria, Sudan, Sierra Leone, Albania, Bangladesh, Turkish occupied Cyprus, Libya, Nicaragua, Great Lakes, Israel or Israeli controlled countries / areas, Liberia, Zaire, Iraq, Iran, C.I.S. / Russian Pacific ports (but bunkering at Nakhoda / Vanino / Vostochny / Shakhtersk only allowed which trading always via normal / customary capsize port(s) during May to October), only bunker for calling Colombo of Sri Lanka, North Korea, Anglo (including Cabinda), former States of Yugoslavia (but Slovenia and Croatia allowed), Namibia, Djibouti, Somalia, Kenya, Ethiopia, Tanzania, Venezuela, Mozambique, Madagascar, Yemen, Eritrea, Sri Lanka, Cambodia, Georgia, Haiti, Cyprus, Finland, Norway, Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, Honduras, Nigeria, Kuwait, Namibia, Salvador, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Orinoco River, Congo (DROC, ROC), Sea of Azov, war and warlike zones declared from time to time by the Joint War Committee of London.

In any case, Vessel cannot trade U.S.A. and Panama Canal.

The Vessel is not allowed at any time to trade to the port / areas which are prohibited from trading by the U.N. and / or International Organization of the U.N. and / or the authorities of the country under whose flag the Vessel is sailing.

No direct sailing between Mainland China and Taiwan.

Basic annual war risk insurance on Hull and Machinery value including I.V. and crew war bonus to be for Owners’ account. In the event, Charterers employ the Vessel in a trade for which there is an additional war risk insurance premium, Charterers to reimburse the Owners such additional premium based on Vessel insured total value including I.V. at that time. Charterers to pay for such additional premium on receipt of Owners’ invoice accompanied by original vouchers from Underwriters. Additional premium charged by Owners Underwriters, shall not exceed amount charged had the Vessel been entered with Lloyds of London Underwriters. Crew war bonus if any, caused by the trade in which Vessel is engaged to be for Charterers’ account.

CONWARTIME 2013 to apply to this Charter Party.

Vessel not to be employed in consecutive shuttle trades but coastal trade always allowed provided not on consecutive voyages.

Vessel will maintain a safe distance off East Coast Africa including Seychelles at Master’s discretion. Vessel shall not be requested to pass West of Madagascar.

Clause for Passing Straits of Magellan / Cape Horn
Vessel is only allowed to trade straits of Magellan / Cape Horn between 15th October and 1st April and only in strict accordance with following Clause:

1)	During the allowed period, Vessel may be routed via straits of Magellan or Cape Horn solely in Master’s option. 
2)	Such voyage will only be from the pacific / feast to the Atlantic.

3)	A Weather Routing Company to be appointed and paid by Charterers in order to keep Master informed of weather conditions prevailing in the area.

4)	Any / all compulsory and non-compulsory pilots, tugs and/or any other services required by Master for safety of Vessel to be for Charterers’ account.

5)	Any additional premium for breaking I.W.L. / IN.L. including crew bonus if required for passing Magellan straits / Cape Horn to be for Charterers’ account.

6)	Master at his sole discretion, in case weather conditions are extremely bad and he considers that it is unsafe to proceed, to have the liberty to slow down or to stop at a safe anchorage and wait until the weather improves. All time lost and bunkers consumed to be for Charterers’ account.

Indian Ocean Transit / Trading Clause:
Notwithstanding the BIMCO Piracy Clause and the CONWARTIME 2013 Clause, which are both applicable to this Clause, Owners agree to transit Red Sea, Gulf of Aden and Indian Ocean on the most direct route subject to any anti-piracy deviation undertaken during any passage which is considered by the Master to be reasonable and necessary when requested by Charterers subject to the following terms.

Charterers’ option to slow steam the Vessel in the piracy zone. Master to maintain the option to increase speed where / when circumstances dictate

Owners have the option before any transit of the Gulf of Aden and/or Indian Ocean to:

Engage a security firm which will provide an armed security team that will work out a security plan with the Vessel’s command and prepare and brief the crew for potential piracy incidents and will taking into account the characteristics of the Vessel, prepare the "hardening" of the Vessel against piracy attacks (e.g. bringing out razor wire and electrical fencing and to arrange armed guards) together with the Vessel’s crew in accordance with best management practice.

The Charterers will reimburse the Owners for the costs of such security firm, initial and replenishment cost of antipiracy material, crew bonus, armed guards fees, and extra insurances (such as extra WRI, LOH and K&R insurance) against original invoices up to maximum USD 80,000.00 (per passage) including crew bonus USD 15,000.00 (per passage). Time spend related armed guards for waiting, boarding, disembarking and deviation to be on Charterer’s account.

The following countries or places are specifically excluded:

Cuba, Lebanon, Syria, Sudan, Sierra Leone, Albania, Bangladesh, Turkish occupied Cyprus, Libya, Nicaragua, Great Lakes, Israel or Israeli controlled countries / areas, Liberia, Zaire, Iraq, Iran, C.I.S. / Russian Pacific ports (but bunkering at Nakhoda / Vanino / Vostochny / Shakhtersk only allowed which trading always via normal / customary capsize port(s) during May to October), only bunker for calling Colombo of Sri Lanka, North Korea, Anglo (including Cabinda), former States of Yugoslavia (but Slovenia and Croatia allowed), Namibia, Djibouti, Somalia, Kenya, Ethiopia, Tanzania, Venezuela, Mozambique, Madagascar, Yemen, Eritrea, Sri Lanka, Cambodia, Georgia, Haiti, Cyprus, Finland, Norway, Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, Honduras, Nigeria, Kuwait, Namibia, Salvador, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Orinoco River, Congo (DROC, ROC), Sea of Azov, war and warlike zones declared from time to time by the Joint War Committee of London.

In any case, Vessel cannot trade U.S.A. and Panama Canal.

The Vessel is not allowed at any time to trade to the port / areas which are prohibited from trading by the U.N. and / or International Organization of the U.N. and / or the authorities of the country under whose flag the Vessel is sailing.

No direct sailing between Mainland China and Taiwan.

Basic annual war risk insurance on Hull and Machinery value including I.V. and crew war bonus to be for Owners’ account. In the event, Charterers employ the Vessel in a trade for which there is an additional war risk insurance premium, Charterers to reimburse the Owners such additional premium based on Vessel insured total value including I.V. at that time. Charterers to pay for such additional premium on receipt of Owners’ invoice accompanied by original vouchers from Underwriters. Additional premium charged by Owners Underwriters, shall not exceed amount charged had the Vessel been entered with Lloyds of London Underwriters. Crew war bonus if any, caused by the trade in which Vessel is engaged to be for Charterers’ account.

CONWARTIME 2013 to apply to this Charter Party.

Vessel not to be employed in consecutive shuttle trades but coastal trade always allowed provided not on consecutive voyages.

Vessel will maintain a safe distance off East Coast Africa including Seychelles at Master’s discretion. Vessel shall not be requested to pass West of Madagascar.
column16:
Owners to provide by fax or email invoice on their headed paper to the Charterers covering each Charterers’ remittance but
such fax or email invoices not to be considered a condition required for hire or other payments and on no occasion are such
payments to be delayed by Charterers on this account when they are due.
column17:
Charterers Bill(s) of Lading (on Congenbill form or equivalent) to be used and Master to release to Charterers or their Agents
his authority to sign Bill(s) of Lading on his behalf provided in strict accordance with Mate’s Receipts and Charterers holding
Owners harmless against all consequences arising out of their signing Bill(s) of Lading.
column19:
Bunkers on delivery to be about 1,500 metric tons of LSFO and about 158 metric tons of LSGO (in case Owners cannot arrange bunkering at Beilun, Owners have the option to arrange bunkering at Zhoushan, the delivery place should be changed to dropping last outward sea pilot Zhoushan, other terms remain unchanged).

Bunkers on redelivery to be about same quantities as on actual delivery.

Bunker prices USD 500.00 per metric ton for LSFO, and USD 550.00 per metric ton for LSGO.

All LSFO above means any fuel that meets IMO 2020 compliant fuel and all bunkers on redelivery shall comply with the requirements of bunker fuel sulphur content 2020.

Owners have the right to bunker Vessel for their own account at loading / discharging or Charterers bunkering port provided will not interfere with Charterers loading / discharging operations and Vessel’s intake, but in the last voyage only.

Bunkers specifications: cancelling
Intermediate fuel oil : RMG35 ISO 8217:2005 or better Marine diesel oil : DMB or DMA ISO 8217:2005 or better

All bunkers delivered not to contain waste lubricating oil, chemical waste or any other substance(s) which are not inherent to bunker. Bunker supplied to be of a homogenous blend.

The Charterers / suppliers to provide Master’s prior bunkering the Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) in IMO-recommended format, as detailed in resolution MSC 282(86) of IMO otherwise all delay, expenses and consequences arising due to Charterers failure to comply with this Clause to be for Charterers account.

Quantity supplied shall be finally determined by sounding of the tanks of the delivering barge or by reading of meters at shore installation.

Owners reserve their right to make a claim against Charterers for any damage to the main engine or the auxiliary engines caused by the use of unsuitable fuels or fuels not complying with the specifications. Additionally, if bunker fuels supplied do not conform with the specification or otherwise prove unsuitable for burning in the Vessel’s main engines or auxiliary engines, the Owners shall not be held responsible for any reduction in the Vessel’s speed performance and/or increased bunker consumption, or any time lost and any other consequences.

Owners and Charterers will work out a best possible solution to resolve if such proven off spec bunkers have already been supplied on board, failing which Owners have the right to order the Vessel to de-bunker the unsuitable fuels remaining on board at Charterers time and expense at a time and place to be mutually agreed between Owners and Charterers.
column20:
Charterers to pay Owners USD 1,500.00 (One Thousand Five Hundred United States Dollars) per 30 days or pro rata for cables / entertainment / victualling charges.

(a)	Black Sea ports: In case Vessel calls any port in the Black Sea region, Charterers to pay Owners USD 5,000.00 in lumpsum for each port of call as compensation for the penalty imposed by port authority regarding the ballast and fresh water issues.

(b)	Additional equipment: Any additional equipment required at ports over and above that which the Vessel has on board (particular reference is made to certain Ports such as in Chile where additional mooring ropes and wires are required over the normal quantity carried on board by the Vessel), to be hired and/or supplied by Charterers at their time and expense.

+T22
column21:
Charterers are to give Owners approximate notice of redelivery area
thence 25 / 20 / 15 / 10 / 7 days’ approximate redelivery date and intended port thence 5/ 3 / 2 / 1 days’ definite notice of redelivery date and port.

Clause 29
Charterers shall furnish the Master from time to time with all requisite instructions and sailing directions in writing and the Master shall keep a full and correct deck and engine logs of the voyage or voyages showing inter alia the course of the Vessel and distance run and the consumption of fuel oil, which is to be patent to the Charterers or their Agents, a true copy of which is to be sent to Charterers immediately after completion of the voyage, when required.


Clause 30 - Bunkers
Bunkers on delivery to be about 1,500 metric tons of LSFO and about 158 metric tons of LSGO (in case Owners cannot arrange bunkering at Beilun, Owners have the option to arrange bunkering at Zhoushan, the delivery place should be changed to dropping last outward sea pilot Zhoushan, other terms remain unchanged).

Bunkers on redelivery to be about same quantities as on actual delivery.

Bunker prices USD 500.00 per metric ton for LSFO, and USD 550.00 per metric ton for LSGO.

All LSFO above means any fuel that meets IMO 2020 compliant fuel and all bunkers on redelivery shall comply with the requirements of bunker fuel sulphur content 2020.

Owners have the right to bunker Vessel for their own account at loading / discharging or Charterers bunkering port provided will not interfere with Charterers loading / discharging operations and Vessel’s intake, but in the last voyage only.

Bunkers specifications: cancelling
Intermediate fuel oil : RMG35 ISO 8217:2005 or better Marine diesel oil : DMB or DMA ISO 8217:2005 or better

All bunkers delivered not to contain waste lubricating oil, chemical waste or any other substance(s) which are not inherent to bunker. Bunker supplied to be of a homogenous blend.

The Charterers / suppliers to provide Master’s prior bunkering the Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) in IMO-recommended format, as detailed in resolution MSC 282(86) of IMO otherwise all delay, expenses and consequences arising due to Charterers failure to comply with this Clause to be for Cha
